<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="72" pageId="8" pageNumber="71" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="71">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="71">
According to M. Kuhlmann, Kiel (pers. comm., 23.11.2015) earlier reports of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Colletes canescens" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canescens">Colletes canescens</taxonomicName>
Smith 1853, from the islands, most likely refer to this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="72" pageId="8" pageNumber="71">
DNA barcoding of specimen B46 (acc. no. KX824776) and BLAST search in GenBank resulted in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Colletes eous" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eous">Colletes eous</taxonomicName>
from Greece as best match (acc. no. EF028501). However, the similarity is only 94%, which means that there are 23 nucleotide differences distributed over the entire COI sequences (see also branch length difference in the ML tree, Fig. 2). 
<pageBreakToken pageId="9" pageNumber="72" start="start">This</pageBreakToken>
suggests that the Azorean 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Colletes" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Colletes</taxonomicName>
is not the same species as the one sequenced from Greece but more morphological and genetic data is needed to solve this question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
